---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import GeneratorShell from '../../components/GeneratorShell.astro';

const title = 'Free Cover Letter Intro Generator | Genfy';
const description = 'Generate the perfect opening for your cover letter. Lead with achievement, not "I am writing to apply". Copy-ready in seconds.';

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org', '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Why is the intro the most important part?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Recruiters decide in 6-10 seconds whether to keep reading or move on. A weak intro kills the letter before the second paragraph.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Why not start with "I am writing to apply"?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'It states obvious info that wastes space. Opening with a concrete achievement or specific data hooks the reader from line one.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Do these templates work for LinkedIn?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes. The same rules apply to LinkedIn messages, Easy Apply notes and direct emails to the hiring manager.' } },
  ],
};
---
<Layout title={title} description={description} lang="en" schema={faqSchema} withSidebar={true}>
  <GeneratorShell lang="en" tag="Work" title="Cover Letter Intro Generator"
    intro="The first line decides whether they keep reading. Generate openers with concrete achievements, specific data or referrals — no clichés.">

    <div slot="tool" class="cl">
      <div class="cl-row">
        <div>
          <label for="cl-role">Role you're applying for</label>
          <input id="cl-role" type="text" value="Senior Marketing Manager" />
        </div>
        <div>
          <label for="cl-company">Company</label>
          <input id="cl-company" type="text" value="Acme Inc." />
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="cl-row">
        <div>
          <label for="cl-years">Years of experience</label>
          <input id="cl-years" type="number" value="6" min="0" max="40" />
        </div>
        <div>
          <label for="cl-area">Primary area</label>
          <input id="cl-area" type="text" value="digital marketing" />
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="cl-row">
        <div>
          <label for="cl-achievement">Best achievement (one sentence)</label>
          <input id="cl-achievement" type="text" value="led the launch of a product that generated $2M in its first year" />
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="cl-row">
        <div>
          <label for="cl-style">Opening style</label>
          <select id="cl-style">
            <option value="achievement">Achievement-led</option>
            <option value="why-here">Why this company</option>
            <option value="referral">Internal referral</option>
            <option value="research">Specific research finding</option>
          </select>
        </div>
      </div>
      <button id="cl-gen" class="btn btn-primary" type="button">Generate 3 versions</button>
      <button id="cl-copy" class="btn btn-ghost" type="button">Copy</button>
      <textarea id="cl-out" rows="14" readonly style="margin-top:1rem;"></textarea>
    </div>

    <div slot="content">
      <h2>The most important rule: lead with the achievement, not the intent</h2>
      <p>
        The most common mistake in cover letters is the opener "I am writing to apply for the
        Marketing Manager role posted on Indeed". That sentence adds nothing the reader doesn't
        know — they're already reading your application, they already know the role. Wasted
        paragraph. The modern professional rule: open with concrete data about you. Your most
        relevant achievement. A number that matters. A specific observation about the company
        that proves you researched.
      </p>

      <h2>Four opener styles that work</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Achievement-led.</strong> "Over the last three years, I led the launch of a product that generated $2M in its first year." Works when your record speaks for itself.</li>
        <li><strong>Why this company.</strong> "I've followed [company]'s work since 2020, and what stood out most was your decision to [concrete fact]." Works for companies you genuinely admire.</li>
        <li><strong>Internal referral.</strong> "[Name], head of [area], suggested I apply after we discussed [topic]." Works when you have a real referral.</li>
        <li><strong>Research finding.</strong> "Reading [company]'s last quarterly report, I noticed segment [X] grew Y%. My experience in [area] aligns directly with that growth." Works for analytical roles.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Data that DOES belong in the intro</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Tangible numbers.</strong> "20% increase", "10 million users", "$500k budget managed".</li>
        <li><strong>Recognizable names.</strong> If you worked at well-known companies or studied at top programs, mention it briefly.</li>
        <li><strong>Time.</strong> "Over 5 years at X" gives more context than "I have experience".</li>
        <li><strong>Comparative scope.</strong> "Team of 3 I scaled to 12" tells more than "led a team".</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Data that does NOT belong in the intro</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Your name (it's on the resume).</li>
        <li>The role you're applying for (they know).</li>
        <li>Where you found the posting (irrelevant for evaluation).</li>
        <li>Your availability (that goes at the end, if anywhere).</li>
        <li>Begging language ("I would appreciate the opportunity to", "looking forward to your prompt response").</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Recommended length</h2>
      <p>
        The ideal intro is 2-3 sentences totaling 35-60 words. Enough to plant a strong data
        point and steer the reader to the next paragraph. Longer dilutes; shorter feels
        truncated. If your best achievement doesn't fit in one sentence, use two — don't
        compress past clarity.
      </p>

      <h2>Tailor to the role</h2>
      <p>
        The achievement you put in the intro must connect with what the role asks for. If the
        posting says "experience leading remote teams", your intro should include a number
        about the size of the remote team you led. If it says "ecommerce experience", your
        intro should carry an ecommerce metric. That alignment is the difference between 100
        identical letters and yours.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div slot="faq">
      <details><summary>Why is the intro most important?</summary><p>Recruiters decide in 6-10 seconds. A weak intro kills the letter.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Why not "I am writing to apply"?</summary><p>Obvious info, wasted space. Opening with achievement creates interest.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Works on LinkedIn?</summary><p>Yes. Same rules for Easy Apply and direct messages.</p></details>
    </div>
  </GeneratorShell>
</Layout>

<style>
  .cl-row { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  @media (max-width: 600px) { .cl-row { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
</style>

<script>
  const roleEl = document.getElementById('cl-role') as HTMLInputElement;
  const companyEl = document.getElementById('cl-company') as HTMLInputElement;
  const yearsEl = document.getElementById('cl-years') as HTMLInputElement;
  const areaEl = document.getElementById('cl-area') as HTMLInputElement;
  const achEl = document.getElementById('cl-achievement') as HTMLInputElement;
  const styleEl = document.getElementById('cl-style') as HTMLSelectElement;
  const out = document.getElementById('cl-out') as HTMLTextAreaElement;
  const genBtn = document.getElementById('cl-gen') as HTMLButtonElement;
  const copyBtn = document.getElementById('cl-copy') as HTMLButtonElement;

  function generate() {
    const role = roleEl.value || '[role]';
    const company = companyEl.value || '[Company]';
    const years = yearsEl.value || 'X';
    const area = areaEl.value || '[area]';
    const ach = achEl.value || '[your top achievement]';
    const s = styleEl.value;
    let lines: string[] = [];
    if (s === 'achievement') {
      lines = [
        `Over my ${years} years in ${area}, I ${ach}. That's why the ${role} opening at ${company} caught my attention: the role lines up almost exactly with the kind of impact I've been building.`,
        `${ach} — that's the line that best defines my last ${years} years in ${area}. When I saw the ${role} role at ${company}, I knew it was the place where that kind of work scales.`,
        `After ${years} years in ${area}, one achievement still defines how I work: ${ach}. That's why I'm applying for the ${role} role at ${company}.`,
      ];
    } else if (s === 'why-here') {
      lines = [
        `I've been following ${company}'s work for a while, and the way you've positioned yourselves over the past year stood out to me. With ${years} years in ${area}, I believe I can contribute exactly to the kind of growth you're building in the ${role} role.`,
        `Few companies in the market think about ${area} the way ${company} does. I'm applying for the ${role} role with ${years} years of experience and one recent achievement I find relevant: ${ach}.`,
        `What sets ${company} apart from most of its category is execution. After ${years} years in ${area}, where I ${ach}, I want to contribute to that kind of work in the ${role} role.`,
      ];
    } else if (s === 'referral') {
      lines = [
        `[Referrer name], from the ${area} team at ${company}, suggested I apply for the ${role} role. After a conversation about the role's challenges, I believe my ${years} years in ${area} (where I ${ach}) match what the team needs.`,
        `Talking with [Referrer name] about ${company}'s 2026 priorities encouraged me to apply for the ${role} role. I bring ${years} years in ${area}, with one connected achievement: ${ach}.`,
        `[Referrer name] sent me the ${role} posting noting that the team specifically needs profiles like mine. With ${years} years in ${area}, my highest-impact case was: ${ach}.`,
      ];
    } else {
      lines = [
        `Reading ${company}'s recent public report, I noticed a concrete move in ${area} that aligns with what I've been doing: ${ach}. That's why I'm applying for the ${role} role, with ${years} years of experience in the field.`,
        `One data point from ${company}'s last year stood out to me and connects with my work: ${ach}. I have ${years} years in ${area} and the ${role} role seems built for profiles with that kind of track record.`,
        `After reading how ${company} is approaching ${area}, I decided to apply for the ${role} role. My recent professional story backs it: ${ach}, after ${years} years in the field.`,
      ];
    }
    out.value = lines.map((l, i) => `Version ${i + 1}:\n${l}`).join('\n\n');
  }
  genBtn.addEventListener('click', generate);
  copyBtn.addEventListener('click', async () => {
    if (!out.value) return;
    await navigator.clipboard.writeText(out.value);
    const t = copyBtn.textContent; copyBtn.textContent = 'Copied!';
    setTimeout(() => { copyBtn.textContent = t; }, 1200);
  });
  generate();
</script>
